      "content": "The expansion of the social safety net has been a significant factor in reducing labor participation, as generous benefits like expanded unemployment insurance and expanded SNAP create a \"benefits cliff\" that disincentivizes taking jobs. Research consistently shows that when the cost of losing benefits outweighs the wage offered by a job, people are less likely to enter or re-enter the workforce, effectively creating a welfare trap that discourages work. This phenomenon is not just a theoretical concern but a documented reality where policy design directly shapes economic behavior by making work less attractive than relying on state support.",
